x4freetext: Scanning scintillation detection online with PC
Ge(Li) detector of large volume - for gamma
activity of activated samples in most of cases.
Efficiency 0.992% for E-gamma 661.6 keV and 0.506% for
High-pure Ge detector with energy resolution
1.8keV at E-gamma 1332 keV and relative efficiency 20%
-for Am-241 measurement and most difficult measurements
Data in 41298 were derived from data
in 41240. Data of Table 1 of RI-252 (derived cross
sections at 14.1 MeV point) are given in Entry 41298 .
Also in Table 5.71 of INDC(CCP)-402,1997 data are
the same as in Table 1 of RI-252,1999.

Of author V.Filatenkov, received 29 March 2013 by
S.Simakov (NDS IAEA), forwarded to CJD 6 April 2013:
"27Al(n,a) cs were taken from the evaluation EAF-4 of
that time.Some explanations should be done to this.
1.  In reality, all the cross sections were measured in
our experiments relatively to the 93Nb(n,2n) c-s (if
other was not pointed out specially).
2.  However, this cross section that is very convenient
for practical use was not evaluated good enough at that
3.  We decided to improve the data of 93Nb(n,2n) using
the ratio of 27Al(n,a) to 93Nb(n,2n) cs measured in the
large body of our experiments. This ratio is shown in
4.  The corrected in such a way data of 93Nb(n,2n) were
finally used as the reference cross section in our
So, in fact, all the data of our measurements are first
However, it would be not quite correctly to write this,
because Al foils were used often, but not in every
measurement. In the contrary, the niobium foils were
used ALWAYS, and namely the 93Nb(n,2n) c-s was used in
This is why the both cross sections, the 27Al(n,a) and
the 93Nb(n,2n) were given in our works as reference
Probably, it would be better to give in the
corresponding Tables of our works three column:
1.  The 27Al(n,a) data taken from the evaluation
2.  The 93Nb(n,2n) to 27Al(n,a) ratio measured by us
3.  The corrected 93Nb(n,2n) cs that is the result of
multiplication of the evaluated 27Al(n,a) data by the
measured ratio, it means the data that were finally
used in our measurements as the reference c-s.
